Rolled back into the coastal mountains // last night with @maude_ct . Our fluid conversation, sharing stories of what brought us to the now, travel experiences, broken hearts, inspiring people met along the way, fell away to silence with the tempo of the setting sun. The sky overhead colored with a faded cold blue that blended seamlessly to lilac purple, then soft pink, then a warmer glow. The horizon, a jagged silhouette of peaks and triangular trees. We agreed that the show in the sky felt like being welcomed home, that the road was a nest in the valley, protected by the power and grace of the mountains. 

Grateful to be home. 
Where I feel most alive.

Thank you @thenorthface_snow for supporting my passion to #neverstopexploring the mountains.

Video: @arcademotion
Full film ALL ACCESS @outsidewatch

Looking forward to watching them grow!

Thank you Sister Summit for making a courageous leap to create this gathering and for the invite to be a part of the first ever event of this kind, of which I’m sure there will be many more.

My love language to give: food. // 

We all took on different chores & responsibilities back at camp in AK. Chopping veggies with a headlamp on after a day out to feed the crew simple nourishing eats, brought me a tremendous amount of happiness.

Another favorite thing about food is how it brings people together. Especially at the end of big day out in the mountains. It’s where the nerves settle, the stories begin to percolate, and the laughs roar. A lot of memorable moments in this teepee.

Holiday cooking marathon complete // 

Truly grateful to be trusted to chef up nourishing eats for family gatherings, to be a fly on the wall, especially around the holidays when family dynamics can be real. 

Feeling blessed to have such cheerful and kind clients from around the world. Thank you for trusting the vegan cheeses & plant based chocolate mousse options. Food is personal, traditions and memories attached, thank you for allowing me to be a part of the experience. 

Now, time to shift gears. Time to shred.

Learning to embody // that to follow what sparks joy, is indeed an act of love, not just for Self, but for humanity. 

For a long time, I’ve been sitting atop the ridge of indecision, one leg dangling in the realm of what it means to be an athlete & the other in the space of what it means to be of service. Instead of embracing that they both belong. 

Sports, especially those that isolate us from family and the generalized cadence of society for days, weeks, months at a time feel to be selfish endeavors. The monkey mind chatters, “how inconsiderate to the whole to chase a feeling?!”, especially when the seasons shift and my partner and I log extended time apart, to fill our surfing and snowboard cups. The risk associated, the imprint it would leave on others, especially if we ever had kids,  if things didn’t go as planned, a layer of Payne’s grey cloud that always hovers at the peak. 

Sweeping the magnifying glass over the fine print in my heart, & pausing over the question of “why”, very often, I’ve sat with... is it 

to be seen?
to be validated?
to be heard?
for the rush? 
an escape?

Part of my humanness says yes sometimes to the above, but the real answer to the big “why” is simply because I can’t not. It’s what some call, “the good karma”. The illuminated path, the energy that swells and swirls in the center of our chests, that says, “this way”. For me, it’s adventure. The GPS works by showing what brings us joy. What lights us up? What cant we live without? The artful intelligence always steering us back on course if we stray, sometimes a j-turn, sometimes the scenic route. A myriad of ways to arrive, the destination pretty darn fixed. It has the map. It is the compass. We just need to learn to listen. Then to trust. Especially when it doesn’t seem completely rational. 

A lifelong practice. 

Following the threads lead by wonder; weaving fabric of passion and purpose. Some of us, are just meant to be in the cathedrals of snow & ice, storms and waves. 

Dropping into acceptance, sure frees up a heck of a lot of energy 😂🤍🙏🏼

Finding purchase on the ridge // praying that the slope doesn’t give way, the rhythmic whoomp-whoomp of the rotor blades swirled stinging shards of ice and snow all around. Falling in any direction, including the intended line down was out of the question.

As Guide @kooshpow met my thumbs up and Pilot @tristanbuhler peeled away, the chaos of the drop-in settled as the belly of the aircraft shrunk out of vision. Testing my footing once again, I gingerly stood up, taking it all in like how it must feel for a gopher to peek up out of a hole blinded by the warmth of the sun and beauty of the landscape, but on alert for any danger or predators. 

Holy shit, how am I here? 

I could feel my heart beating, the walls of my chest expanding a bit further than ever before. Lit up undulations of snow caked rocks made up the spines to the front 180 degrees of my vision, behind me everything dropped down in the shadows with lower convex rolls ending into places the imagination chose to avoid.

The thrill of the toe-in and the knowing that I now was committed to riding down was setting in. The elixir of fear matched with excitement — fight, flight, freeze….or shred.

Come back to your breath. 
Back to the belly breath. 
Back into your body. 
Set fear on the shelf. 
Focus on the present. 
Focus on what you need to do.

This is the sequence of self-talk I go through when I’ve managed to stretch past the steady hum of comfort. This is the pillar of why I seek adventure.

I burst into laughter, into the knowingness that I chose this.

I’m here to get uncomfortable, 
to meet my fear, 
to learn, 
to grow.

This is the snowy version of a maloka to me, one of the places where I get to expand my wingspan and learn how to open my heart further to feel the entire gamut of human emotions. To feel, is what it means to be alive.

Thank you @kooshpow for supporting us on the journey & trusting in our visions.

Thank you @tristanbuhler for being a total badass and getting us out and onto these lines.

Big news for the ladies // whose hearts yearn to push the boundaries of human potential in the world’s most challenging environments…

Today, The North Face is introducing the first Himalayan Suit designed specifically for women. Whoop whoop!

In this redesign, the women’s suit has been engineered to provide the fit and considerations women need for mountain exploration. The suit is designed to allow for freedom of movement and built for women’s bodies featuring torso and inseam lengths designed specifically for their form.

The fit is a big deal, but the even bigger deal is how this speaks to the movement that there is an increase in women wantiung to to step up and step into this world of exploration in the mountains.Proud to be behind a brand that sees this and is fueling the gosh darn revolution. 

I’ve been on a bit of a Himalayan research reading binge this past year. The whisper of wonder on a goggle search lead me to order a stack of books. The first of which was @kitdski ‘s book, seeing a woman on the cover was the hook.

What will come from this pull, we will see. But what I can say is these reads continue to feed the mindset and heart compass that never falters to point to living a life of adventure.

These books have also offered a shift in perspective around the limitless potential of humans; and really a jolt of inspiration and validation that time spent out on the edge of the unknown yields far more than just bragging rights of a summit or a line - it’s really all about the journey. And we need more women out there!

Respect to the women who have graced the mountains before & paved the steps; who are currently charging; those who will follow those footsteps and push beyond. 

Let’s keep redefining what’s possible 🤍

A few reads if you’re interested:

• Higher Love, by: @kitdski 

•The Third Pole, 
by: @m_synnott

•Into This Air, 
by @krakauernotwriting 

•Training for the New Alpinism
by: Steve House & Scott Johnson

by Bernadette McDonald

Life is meant to be a progression not an exercise in perfection. //

I’m speaking to a mirror, when I say this. 

The majority of pithy expressions and rambling rants that I share are just me trying to find nuggets of truth in this journey of life. I have not yet reached nirvana, ha! I share with the hope that if someone finds a commonality in my blueprint to their own, maybe it’ll be of service to them to move through their own mountain pass with less fumbling and bruises.

For me, big places with powerful energy emphasize the potency of experiences, like the mountains and oceans, especially Alaska.

Settling into being home from a blur of nearly 2 months up in the last frontier. As I continue to sort through the happenings of this winter — the big opportunities, the feelings of support and validation on my trajectory in the mountains, the shadow work that lies in the sandy bottoms of the ebbs— there’s no surprise that there’s quite the box to sort through. Integration takes time and patience.

I’ve been processing; napping, sleeping-in without guilt, listening to my body when it says slow down, journaling, breathing, meditating, isolating, painting, doubling down on dog walks in the 100 shades of greens, browns, and greys that is the pantone of home. Digesting what I needed to compartmentalize in the moment and drawing in the nectar of it all. From the joyful moments, the connections with incredible people, the bliss, the highs, the moments on the edge, the conversations and communion with fear, the visceral “yes” moments where quite literally the soul breathes. And giving space, taking notes, and reframing my self-talk verbiage where I didn’t pause before speaking, took a reserved approach instead of opening it up on a line, let ego or fear take the wheel. It all deserves space…

Hello sunshine // Welcoming in the transition of seasons in the mountains with open arms, even though @anna_segal & I were super jazzed to get a ski spring mission in together. Mother Nature chose sun over snow, so we made a quick pivot from snow to rock. Sometimes you gotta go with flow. 

Thanks for the fun week of climbing everyone!

A slice of paradise // The exploration of the west coast continues, except this time the vehicle was the art of collaborating with plants & animals as food & medicine. 

I believe that food is more than just sustenance - it’s a way to connect with others, to share experiences, and to create memories. 

Thank you Oyster Island Retreat for the invitation to be a part of your summer opener; for the opportunity to be inspired by the serenity of being isolated on the island and the raw beauty of nature that surrounds. 

This place is magic and I feel so lucky to have taken a shot to translate that vibe into the food.

I’ve been ruminating // on how multidimensional we all are as human beings. The essence of the soul stays the same, but different parts of us need to show up in different scenarios. The warrior energy that is embedded while standing a top of a snowboard line, is vastly different the vibration necessary for showing up for the people that we love in a compassionate way. Undoubtably there are moments where these segments crossover, a tornado of colours, not a proportionate rainbow emoji. The ongoing craft seems to be in finding the rhythm of calling in what we need when we need it; and turning the frequency off when it’s time to make a shift. And of utmost importance, how are we able to get outta the way to let the conduit happen?!

My answer for one of the parts, a big bright art studio. Environment! Feng shui. But that’s another conversation.

This past week I was able to reconnect with an array of friends. Each interaction was different, each left me feeling inspired and grateful. We talked about everything from art to plant medicines, surfing to conscious tourism, foraging to neuroscience. We walked on beaches, shared meals, played in fields of buttercups, surfed, and relished in the simple joys of the beauty of deep conversations, nature, and friendship.

As I leave the island walkabout (more like runaround), I’m struck by the truth in Ram Dass' words that we are "walking each other home." Each interaction, each relationship, serves as a spark of inspiration to guide us back to our true selves, all of our parts. Especially the relationships we feel drawn to, the intense bonds, almost like we’ve lived a previous life, or many for that matter, are in a sense our guides. Leading us back into remembrance of who we truly are.

Thank you for inspiring me and reminding me of the beauty and complexity of what it means to be humans on this wild ride, and the importance of nourishing friendships. I am grateful for each and every one of you.

With love and gratitude,
T

Climbing feels like catharsis // for limiting beliefs. 

The chitter-chatter of fear can pop-up before even leaving the ground, at least for me. Of course, there’s a strength, a safety, and an efficiency (acquired by dedication) to it; those that are elite dance up the wall with ease. It’s marvelous to witness. The biggest necessity, from the vantage point of the green climber, feels like the steadiness of the voice between the ears. The inner-confidence & trust. But isn’t that the case for most things? How we speak to ourselves matters, the true test is in a space of stress, when we have the perception that our life is on the line. When we can make a spiritual payment of a limiting belief, we make more space for possibility. At least in my opinion ;)

What will be born from a summer further focused in on the art of clambering up rock? :) We’ll see.

When @dghenkel passed away, there was a whisper in my heart to fully immerse myself in climbing. I wanted to honour the time he took to share with me what it felt like to witness the world from a different vantage point. To then translate that into the snowier months. I guess, that time is now. 

I’m a beginner, eager to learn, with a climbing objective in sight, that I’d like to keep in the privacy of my ❤️ for now, but what I can share is that it will be an ode to Dave.  
Miss you dear friend. Honouring you today from the tailgate of my truck, aka Casa di Mango, tucked below the grandiose formation of granite that you so joyfully catapulted many of us into your climbing world. The unwavering trust you had in our inner courage (often invisible to us), be it on snow or rock, continues to send me into waves of celebration and sorrow. Your sparkle continues to significantly inspire the trajectory of my snowboard career. I believe that one of your super powers, one of the greatest gifts you shared with the world was to believe in your friends, lift them up. And to prioritize experiences over things, always. 

Thanks for sand-bagging us and showing us winter mountain people what it feels like to “get small” in the summer. 

Eyes are peeled to see you in the sky, awaiting the noble caw caw that it’s time to send it.

Xo

The Dressed up Pep // because nourishment need not to be compromised by outdoor living.

This is a step-up from one of my favorite road trip & crag snacks, a juicy, delicious red pepper.

This avocado stuffed bell was born from cooking without a full kitchen or fridge the past few weeks, since we’ve been embracing dirt bagging while truck camping. I was looking for ways to keep the veggie quota high, a chance to create less food and packaging waste; and any way to avoid washing dishes.

The pepper is the perfect vehicle for delivery of the healthy fat rich avocado and keeps pretty well outside of the fridge. The spicy mustard gives it a nice kick & the hemp hearts provide some omegas & a protein punch. The edible flowers are a bonus, often in abundance where adventure exists and overlooked. Just be mindful that the flora is indeed safe to nosh on.

Wanna see more recipe tips like this?

•bell pepper
•avocado 
•spicy mustard 
•hemp hearts 
•bonus: edible flowers

It’s been a summer full of movement, up and down the west coast, a year of it really. From Haines, to Valdez, Petersburg AK to chase snowy dreams; Squamish up to Bridge River to cook; Pemberton to Bella Coola, immersed in the humbling power of big mountains; Cumberland to Oyster Island, where you can feel the salty air healing you from the inside out. It’s been everything but stagnant. Finding our feet and paws rooted to where we land, different each week. At times messy, others immediate. Quiet spaces, sounds of nature, a fridge… help expedite the process. Embracing the freedom and flow of opportunities, while navigating the weather of continuous uncertainty. A reminder that even with a home base, we never really know what’s around the corner. Wherever we land, for however long, there’s a sameness on the inside; full of the spectrum of emotion and felt experience, humanness. 

Buckling into life to catch the winds of what it means to Live. With the knowing that , the universe has always got our backs. Grateful this little lady has been able to be by my side for the majority of the travels. Dog love, unconditional, how lucky we are to receive and adventure alongside. 

Mango says, “as long as there is love, safety, food, and a ball, I’m happy.”

I’m taking notes from this furry bodhisattva. 

Photo: @alimarieparker 

#neverstopexploring

In AK // while filming for ALL ACCESS we were super lucky to have clear skies the majority of the trip. By day 6 into the second high pressure, my body was feeling the long, cold days & colder nights. Arms were going numb in the night, hands were cramping on the big hill climbs, and frost nipped, swollen toes were starting to hurt to brush up on the delicate sleeping bag nylon. But on a trip like this, and in life, there are moments when opportunity is illuminated, and you dig deep and go! The wind might have dismantled the pow on our shred objectives, but the sled conditions stayed primo. Getting really excited to sled shred and explore soon with the mountain fam.

Two of my favourite people to dark start in the mountains with // @tatummonod & @ianmcintosh 
 Choosing the right companions for mountain adventures is crucial. Factors such as risk tolerance, ability, good vibes, and similar objectives greatly impact the experience. 

Surrounding ourselves with compatible individuals ensures safety, enjoyment, and a successful journey. Who do you want to celebrate with, but also suffer—mountain exploration realities. So, choose wisely!   Whether it’s a 15 hour day spring mission or hanging out in the clouds freezing; doubling up some cowboy ridges or sharing the joy of party lapping lines. Grateful to spend time in some of the most beautiful mountains with these two badass, kind, hilarious and incredible humans. 

Can you guess who was skeptical if a 430am was an early enough start time?

Photo: @robinoneill

Memories of Petersburg, Alaska // this past spring. 

Storm factor high, crew vibe even higher. 

I heard rumors that the weather in the area was coined as volatile. We had multiple storm systems come through, enough precipitation to ride, but the freezing levels didn’t hold. We watched the amphitheater of objectives cascade like hundreds of waterfalls around us when the sun peeked out, escorted in with the screech of seagulls. The birds were our alarms that sunny skies were there, along with the cease of flapping nylon walls, what it must be like to be a popcorn kernel when the microwave timer is up. With each release of snow above, we sunk into the knowing that our plans would be locked off to the perimeter of camp. The mountains were speaking clearly, “do not enter”. It can’t be expressed enough, the positive nature of the crew that kept spirits from totally plummeting. You guys rock. It always comes down to the people, to community, above all else. I mean, riding big mountain lines with this crew would have been a great way to connect, kindred sprits in the sense of loving skiing and riding and exploring wild places. The riding is always the bonus. Mother Nature makes the calls and this adventure became less about connecting with the nature via flowing up and down the curvatures of pow, and more about feeling the power and energy of the storms by digging, lots of digging, and playing Risk behind tent walls. 

It’s all part of the process. 

Grateful to @thenorthface_snow & @smartwool for keeping me warm. Thankful for the invite to have been along for the ride with this team  @tetongravity! I believe we need a rebate! Where to next?

Vancouver Island friend fam appreciation post //

A handful of my very best friends now live only a few blocks away. They take up the majority of the list of people that are my speed dial. Those that I lean into when the storm of life rages and I’m holding on by a finger tip.
We’ve sat with each other in the muck of the mud of life countless times and celebrated an abundance of lotus blooms, symbolizing the joys of existence, over the last 10 to almost 20 years…

Gratitude for these kinds of friendships— through thick and thin.

Love you all.
Thank you for the visit xo.

Sardinia, Italy // easy to see why it’s been listed as one of the Blue Zones—a geographic area with lower rates of chronic diseases and a longer life expectancy. The energetic pace here moves as smooth as gelato. Low stress, high enjoyment of the present moment.

Thankful, inspired, intimidated, joyful to be here with the @northface family. 

Every single person is not only kind-hearted but also incredibly humble despite their remarkable accomplishments. It feels surreal to be in the mix with this crew, sharing unforgettable experiences and continuing to incubate ideas to push our limits together.

A heartfelt thank you to @thenorthface for bringing us all together for the chance to deepen existing relationships and spark new ones in such a breathtaking place. The bonds we've formed through our shared adventures are truly special, and I can't wait to see where our journeys take us next. 

Big love to you all.
Thank you for the magic Sardinia.
Thank you @highcamp.us crew for taking such great care of us.

Giant Beasts, Tiny People // Link in bio to WATCH the film.

Helicopter access in Alaska has been on my bucket list for close to a decade. When @bigairmare called me up last February to film for her project in partnership with @thenorthface_snow , I was totally taken aback. The emotional reaction to the realization of a long-held dream hit me.

It was a visceral remembrance that in life, seeds planted do sprout. These things take time, often much longer than anticipated, to actualize. It felt like a gentle tap on the shoulder from life, reminding of the power found when we let go and lean into trusting that things will unfold.

What a freaking privilege it was to have had the chance to film with this crew and to get further acquainted with the mountains near Haines. These peaks and valleys possess an energy, a pull that is straight up otherworldly.

Thank you for the invite to join in on your incredible vision Mary, to think that our seed planted in the heaving waters of the pacific down in Mexico would have led us to this is a testament to dream big baby. Alex, Con, Pash, you guys are masters behind the lens and joys to spend time in the mountains with, thank you for the chats and laughs—the banter 10/10. @ianmcintosh big love to you, your wisdom in the mountains, and your celebration of the feminine, in sport, and in the world. AK Heli family thank you for your genuine hospitality. @kooshpow for your positivity and guiding us to the goods. @tristanbuhler you are a total boss, thank you for toeing us into the lines.

Alaska, Mother Earth, thank you.
So much love for you all.

I sat next to a man on the plane //  with soft, brown eyes, swollen with tears behind a curtain of shoulder length white hair. His voice shook as he shared that he was moving back to Victoria, that he had a tent if he couldn’t find a place to live right away. His partner, who had been battling cancer for the last 14 years, had passed away, he found her, and couldn’t stay in the apartment, he knew it would drive him to madness with pain.

I helped him manage the digital screen in front of him. He put his scratchy airline ear buds in, and tuned into the film, The Pope's Exorcist. 

I’ve been thinking a lot about what it means to really sit in the dark. The idea of impermanence keeps my chin above water, the life vest in the sinking sludgy sandy swirls of despair. I’m concerned about the fear and pain that’s manifested in the world as hate, and lived out as violence. I googled one night, wide awake again at 2am, if the grieving sensation from a broken heart, could actually break it. Which apparently, it can. That's powerful energy. In those uncomfortable moments, I can empathize why as a society we seek a life devoid of discomfort. That to medicate with consumption of entertainment, alcohol, drugs; reaches for excess in food, exercise; or a calendar filled to the brim so there’s no space to process, is normalized. The mechanism of avoidance, the goal to not feel. It makes sense.

Once again, the focus of global broadcasters puts the heart in the vice for humanity. The dissonance of it all, unsettling. Closer to home, transitions that feel too soon, friends losing their partners to illnesses and accidents. Identities questioned with jarring career changes. So many relationships coming to an end. There are a lot of people holding on mentally by a thread under the weight of the suffering aspect of what it means to be human. Fuck. 

I often wonder, in the avenue of my own personal beliefs, “we really chose to incarnate here?”

When I was younger, I ran away from feeling, because I felt so much. The last decade, I’ve been relearning, with support, how take down the walls I built around my heart…[continued in comments]

Activism for Mother Earth comes in many forms // @parley.tv X @talisker 

“The ice on our Earth holds some of the longest records of our climate history. Changes in climate that get recorded in the ice tell a story that we can’t see with our own eyes,” says ice core scientist Dr.Alison Criscitiello. 

Last year, @alisoncriscitiello @gerglong and myself embarked on an adventure north of Whistler B.C. with the purpose of reconnecting with nature and absorbing the ancient information that’s often right in front of us. 

This excursion was undertaken in support of Talisker and Parley’s ongoing partnership, and the release of Talisker Glacial Edge 45-Year-Old whisky, its “wildest yet” on account of the unique production process. Twelve casks were taken to the beautiful frozen lands of Canada’s ice fields where they were left exposed to sub-zero temperatures and biting Arctic winds for 96 hours. The extreme cold fractured the wood, so upon coopers reconstructing these unique casks, they had increased surface area for the whisky to interact with during the finishing period in Scotland. 

A portion of the proceeds from the sale of the whisky will go back towards Talisker and Parley’s continuing efforts to support the protection and preservation of ocean ecosystems around the world.

If you have the opportunity to taste this special whiskey, please sip to savour and drink responsibly. xo

When a daydream comes to life //

But seriously, I dedicated much of my time on the meditation cushion to this very moment for 3 years. 

Almost every morning, I would immerse myself in the imagined sensation of riding a proper AK spine. I would envision the rise and fall of my chest before dropping in, the sound of the billowing snow, the sinking of my back foot and the rising of the nose of the board as an impression was left on the snow. I would imagine the feeling of floating, the overwhelming sense of smallness in the vast mountains, and the visual drop-off on either side. There was a felt sense of the energy of the crew, @robinvangyn and @elenahight popped into the dream.

In 2020, it seemed like my vision was about to come true, but then, as we all know, the world went on pause. In 2022, some pieces of the puzzle fell into place, an incredible trip to a different part of Alaska, of which Robin was on the crew, but we didn't get to ride those coveted spines. Then, in 2023, it all came together on trip lead by @bigairmare . It was only yesterday that I realized what I had been replaying in my mind's eye had actually happened. 

The first half of the line, the part I would constantly replay, happened, minus an air. And the essence of the people, the friends, they were only a few days out to arriving in AK at the very same heli op.

Manifestation, co-creations, visions, dreams, call them what you will... they are possible! Details may get shifted, but the power of possibility is very much alive.

What you think,
you become.
What you feel,
you attract.
Want you imagine,
you create.
-Buddha

So, don’t quit you daydream. And a friendly reminder to think beautifully, of others, of the world, and yourself.

@lilymeola sang it best. Her song is a great music motivator, if you’re looking for one.

“Life is not a journey to the grave with the intention of arriving safely in a pretty and well-preserved body, but rather to skid in broadside, thoroughly used up, totally worn out, and loudly proclaiming, ‘Wow, what a ride!’” -Hunter S. Thompson 

Feeling fortunate to be here, 36 revolutions around the radiant sun, and at least 50 if not 60 or 70 laps to go. A lot of living left to do & no time to be squandered. 

Let’s go ❤️
